es a diverse set of institutions including tafthartley pension funds insurance companies foundations and highnetworth individuals it also includes a number of existing and new investors from asia the middle east europe north and south america structured as an annual series with a singleyear investment period the fund is designed to target private credit investments around the globe “the opportunity in the private credit market is meaningful and we expect it to continue to evolve and grow” drew schardt managing director and global head of the private credit team at hamilton lane said in a statement “we believe the strategic opportunities series provides our clients with a flexible credit solution and unique access to these highquality private market transactions” he added a recent survey conducted by hamilton lane revealed that nearly twothirds of lps planned to increase allocations to private credit this appetite it said was reflected in the strong demand for its  fund “lps are being thoughtful in their approach to credit and the structure of this fund aims to deliver a high level of flexibility and optionality while still enabling them to leverage the hamilton lane platform” emily nomeir principal and cohead of the product management group explained hamilton lane has long been an active investor in targeted strategies including creditoriented direct investments and coinvestments while the fund represents the third dedicated vehicle of its kind it is an extension of the company’s broader credit platform in total hamilton lane has about  billion in credit assets under management its secondary fund iv lp – closed at  billion last week – is its biggest secondary fund to date it was launched in  with an initial fundraising target of  billion the size of the secondary fund more than doubles the corpus of the preceding vehicle hamilton lane secondary fund iii which closed at  million in  also read hamilton lane closes its largest secondary fund at b hamilton lane beefs up